<P>12. In 1999 the plaintiff was offered a contract of employment with 3395022 Canada Inc. <BOLD>(&ldquo;3395022&rdquo;),</BOLD> a duly incorporated hygiene services company which provided the plaintiff's services, and those of other dental hygienists, to Dr. Kutcher's practice. The plaintiff signed a written employment agreement dated May 5, 1999 with 3395022 as her employer. <BOLD>[Exhibit 1&mdash;Employment Agreement dated May 5, 1999, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-1, pp. 142&ndash;144]</BOLD> This document is not relevant to the appeal. The appellant accepts the Trial Judge's finding in regard to this document.</P>
<P>13. Via letter dated March 28, 2005, the plaintiff tendered her resignation effective July 7, 2005 [3 <TEXTFRAC>1/2</TEXTFRAC> months notice]. <BOLD>[Exhibit 2&mdash;Letter of resignation, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-2, p. 145]</BOLD> The resignation was accepted. Her resignation was based upon the fact that she (a) was engaged to marry a dentist who resided and practiced in Guelph, (b) she had already moved to Guelph and had been commuting from there to Stoney Creek while still working for 3395022; and (c) she had accepted a term employment contract to fill in for a maternity leave in another dentist's office in Guelph.
