<P>15. In late June 2005 the plaintiff asked to be rehired by 3395022 as her personal situation had changed. Although the defendant had spent monies advertising the position, had received resumes and had interviewed other candidates, to accommodate her request, and because Dr. Kutcher recognized the plaintiff's superior skills as a hygienist, he discussed the matter with his wife, the principal of 3395022, and she prepared a new employment agreement which was then presented to the plaintiff. The plaintiff executed it on June 30, 2005. In this instance the employer was again 3395022 Canada Inc. Justice Chiappetta made a specific finding that <EM>&ldquo;the plaintiff was presented with and signed an employment agreement... which limited the liability of 399, should it terminate the plaintiff without cause, to notice or payment in lieu of notice in accordance with the ESA&rdquo;</EM>. She also noted the conflict in the evidence between the respondent and Dr. Kutcher in respect of the effect of that new agreement.
