<P>17. 3395022 had been created and used as a hygiene services company at a time when dentists were not permitted to incorporate professional corporations. This necessitated the use of multiple entities and more complicated accounting and administrative practices. A decision was made, after the legislation was changed, to: (a) set up a professional corporation [in 2006]; (b) wind up 3395022 [in 2011] and (c) employ the hygienists through the professional corporation [in 2012].</P>
<P>18. The plaintiff was given three months advance notice, via letter dated October 1, 2011, that 3395022 was being wound up and that her employment with that entity would come to an end effective December 31, 2011. In accordance with the provisions of the then current employment agreement [the June 30, 2005 agreement], the plaintiff was given notice of termination. It was in excess of the statutory requirements provided for in the employment agreement. She was given 3 months' notice [13 weeks vs the notice of 6 weeks required under the provisions of the <EM>Employment Standards Act, 2000</EM>&mdash;at that time as per the June 30, 2005 employment agreement]. In fact, as Dr. Kutcher testified, without cross-examination or contradiction on the point, the staff, including the plaintiff, were made aware of the planned change prior to October 1, 2011.
<P1><BOLD>Letter, dated October 1, 2011, from Merren Kutcher [on behalf of 3395022 Canada Inc., Exhibit 16, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;16, p. 187</BOLD></P1>
