<P>20. Following the notice of termination of her employment, referenced above, the plaintiff was offered employment by Kutcher Dentistry Professional Corporation, an incorporated entity operated by Dr. Kutcher. The plaintiff was given a draft copy of a new employment agreement and she was invited to consider the offer and seek whatever advice or counsel she chose.</P>
<P>21. The plaintiff executed the new employment agreement on December 22, 2011. In doing so, the plaintiff executed the third page, initialed both the first and second pages and specifically initialed two paragraphs on the second page where deletions had been made.
<P1><BOLD>Employment Agreement, executed December 22, 2011, Exhibit 6, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-6, pp. 151&ndash;153</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>22. The plaintiff advised Dr. Kutcher, and others, that before accepting and executing the new employment agreement, she and two other hygienists [Lynn Graham and Linda Herechuk] had sought and obtained independent legal advice with respect to the terms and conditions of the new employment agreement. The plaintiff and Ms. Graham accepted an employment offer. Ms. Herechuk did not.
<P1><BOLD>Memorandum, dated March 16, 2012</BOLD> [as to the plaintiff's signature] <BOLD>and March 19, 2012</BOLD> [as to Lynn Graham's signature], <BOLD>Exhibit 17&mdash;Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;17, p. 188</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>23. On cross-examination the plaintiff confirmed (a) having sent a copy of the draft employment agreement to a lawyer [Julie Berridge of Mills &amp; Mills]; (b) having, with Ms. Graham and Ms. Herechuk, sat in her car outside the dental office and discussed the draft agreement on speakerphone with Ms. Berridge; (c) based upon the advice she received from Ms. Berridge, having requested, to which Dr. Kutcher agreed, the deletion of the provision which required her to give at least 8 weeks' notice if she was leaving <BOLD>[Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 8-6, p. 152, second paragraph];</BOLD> and (d) having signed the agreement.</P>
<P>24. The requirement of 8 weeks' notice from the respondent if she resigned was deleted at her request. It had been included in the contract because of the difficulty of dentists finding qualified replacement hygienists in Southern Ontario because it was a good market for hygienists. As Dr. Kutcher testified: <EM>&ldquo;I wanted to have a fair bit of notice in order to look to replace them, because it was getting tougher to find hygienists and that if they were to leave at the last minute I wanted&mdash;this was a basically a disincentive to have them kind of walk out.&rdquo;</EM>
<P1><BOLD>Transcript, evidence of Dr. Kutcher, p, 205, lines 20&ndash;25, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7-F, p. 119</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>25. Dr. Kutcher testified, on cross-examination, that the deletion in the fourth paragraph [page 2 of the agreement], which was an eight week termination notice by the employer to Ms. Theberge, was at his initiation. He explained that the rationale for removal of this eight week notice provision by the employer was because he had expressed to the plaintiff his concerns about (a) her more regular than usual tardiness and (b) her continuing to discuss with and selling Max International supplements [what she called in her evidence &ldquo;nutraceuticals&rdquo;] to patients during hygiene appointments. He further explained that he told the plaintiff she had to demonstrate her commitment to the practice and its patients. She acknowledged and agreed with his concerns and initialed this deletion.</P>
<P>26. Lynn Graham confirmed that she and her two colleagues had received legal advice from Ms. Berridge, as described by Ms. Theberge in her evidence on cross-examination.
