<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;Issues on the Appeal</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Preliminary Matters</EM></TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>A&mdash;Who is / was the Employer?</TI>
<P>31. It is clear, and acknowledged, that at the time of the plaintiff's termination on December 20, 2012 her employer was Kutcher Dentistry Professional Corporation. However, throughout her employment she had three different employers. [1] Dr. Victor Kutcher, operating as a sole practitioner from 1993 to 1997; [2] 3395022 Canada Inc., from 1997 to December 31, 2011; and [3] Kutcher Dentistry Professional Corporation, from January 1 to December 20, 2012.</P>
<P>32. It has been well established, since the House of Lords' decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Salomon v. Salomon</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>&ldquo;That beginning is found in the House of Lords' decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Salomon v. Salomon &amp; Co. Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1895-9] All E.R. 33</CITE><COURTJUR>H.L.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, which established that a company, once legally incorporated, must be treated like any other independent person, with rights and liabilities appropriate to itself. From time to time, litigants have sought to lift this &ldquo;corporate veil&rdquo;, by seeking to make principals of the corporation liable for the obligations of the corporation. However, where, as here, the plaintiff relies upon establishing an independent cause of action against the principals of the company, the corporate veil is not threatened and the Salomon principle remains intact.&rdquo; per Carthy J A, in <CASEREF><SOC>ADGA Systems International Ltd. v. Valcom Ltd.</SOC><CITE>1999 CanLII 1527</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> that the identity of a corporate entity and its shareholders or others associated with it are legally separate and distinct. This decision is regularly cited in reference to cases where the issue is the manner in which business people structure their business affairs through the use of corporate entities. The principle is referred to as the &ldquo;corporate separateness principle&rdquo;. It was recently applied by this Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Yaiguaje v. Chevron Corporation</SOC><CITE>2018 ONCA 472</CITE></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>33. 3395022 Canada Inc. <BOLD>[&ldquo;3395022&rdquo;]</BOLD> was set up and used as a hygiene services company to, inter alia, employ dental hygienists at a time when dentistry professionals were not able to use professional corporations to operate their practices.</P>
<P>34. 3395022 was properly structured and properly operated. All proper record keeping and legislatively required filings were made. It served as the plaintiff's employer for a period of time and sometime after professional corporations were permitted for the dental profession its use was no longer necessary and having only a professional corporation simplified accounting and administrative processes and the structure was accordingly changed. When that occurred, the plaintiff, and the other hygienists were given 3 months' notice of termination by 3395022 prior to its windup and the hygienists were then offered employment with Kutcher Dentistry Professional Corporation. If, as the Trial Judge held, the June 30, 2005 contract was not binding, which is disputed, this constituted a dismissal with combined notice of 15 months comprised of: (a) 3 months prior notice [October 1, 2011 through December 31, 2011] and (b) continued employment for another 12 months [January 1, 2012 through December 31, 2012].</P>
<P>35. There was nothing improper in this arrangement. Professional advice, both legal and accounting / tax, was sought and followed in the structuring of the business.
