<P1><BOLD>Evidence of Dr. Victor Kutcher, uncontroverted and not challenged, Transcript, p. 185, line 9 thru p. 187, line 32, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7-F, pp. 98&ndash;101</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>B&mdash;Credibility of the Evidence</TI>
<P>36. The plaintiff's evidence in this matter must be viewed with doubt and skepticism based upon the following.
<P1>(a) Her failure to address, either in her Statement of Claim, or by way of Reply to the Statement of Defence: (i) the two prior employment agreements <BOLD>[Exhibit 1&mdash;Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-1, pp. 142&ndash;144 and Exhibit 3&mdash;Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-3, pp. 146&ndash;148];</BOLD> (ii) her resignation of her employment on March 28, 2005 <BOLD>[Exhibit 2, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-2, p. 145];</BOLD> (iii) the fact that she had legal advice <BOLD>[Exhibit 17, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;17, p. 188];</BOLD> or (iv) the three months advance notice of termination she received in October 2011 <BOLD>[Exhibit 16, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;16, p. 187].</BOLD> Moreover, none of these documents were produced by the plaintiff for discovery or in her document brief for trial.</P1>
<P1>(b) Deciding not to call Linda Herechuk as a witness, then attempting to give Ms. Herechuk's evidence via hearsay. <BOLD>[Transcript, p. 25, line 17 thru p. 27, line 28, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7-B, pp. 36&ndash;38]</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(c) Insisting that the Max International business, and the income generated from it, were entirely her husband's business and income. The evidence showed that (i) she was actively involved in the Max International business all along and (ii) that during the period following her termination, neither of them had reported / claimed any income from the business. <BOLD>[Exhibit 9A - plaintiff's 2013 T1 Income Tax Return, 2013 Tax Summary&mdash;comparison of her and her husband's 2013 returns, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-9, p.165]</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(d) Both Dr. Kutcher and Leslie Feaver testified that the plaintiff was selling product in the dental office despite express direction not to do so. There is direct conflict between the plaintiff's evidence on this issue and Ms. Feaver's evidence which is supported by her written notes regarding what she observed on November 28, 2012 <BOLD>[Exhibit 25&mdash;handwritten notes of Leslie Feaver dated November 29, 2012, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;25, p. 201]</BOLD> The Trial Judge made the finding that <EM>&ldquo;She</EM> [the plaintiff] <EM>also spoke to Dr. Kutcher's patients about Max products from 2010 until her termination.&rdquo;</EM> <BOLD>[Reasons para 54]</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(e) While claiming that she did not sell Max International products directly to individuals, thereby denying she, or her husband, had any &ldquo;retail customer income&rdquo;, she readily acknowledged that she regularly received shipments of Max International product at the dental office. <BOLD>[Transcript, p. 102, line 28 through p. 103, line 4, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7-B, p. 68 - 69]</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(e) When asked, on discovery, to confirm whether she and her husband used the same tax preparer, the plaintiff denied that was the case but undertook to make an inquiry of Lou Stranges [her tax preparer] and subsequently advised that he did not prepare her husband's tax returns. Notwithstanding this, she removed from her 2013 Tax Return in her document brief for trial a copy of the letter from Mr. Stranges which accompanied the production of her 2013 T1 Tax Return. <BOLD>[Exhibit 22, November 16, 2017 letter from Lou Stranges to Jasmine Theberge and Hughcliffe Lindsay, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;22, p. 198]</BOLD> This letter contains considerable detail concerning Hughcliffe Lindsay's 2013 T1 Income Tax Return, as does <BOLD>Exhibit 9A at Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-9, p. 165</BOLD>. It should be noted that her husband did not disclose any income from Max International sales either. <BOLD>[Reasons at para 55]</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(f) Having testified, in chief, that following the termination she was too emotionally upset to look for work <BOLD>[Transcript, p. 30, line 20 thru p. 31, line 32, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7-B, pp. 39-40]</BOLD>, the plaintiff was forced, on cross-examination, to admit that at the time in issue, January 2013, she was actively engaged in promoting Max International products through a series of events involving her being on conference telephone calls and direct contact with numerous people <BOLD>[Transcript, p. 112, line 30 thru p. 116, line 30, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7-B, pp. 70&ndash;74].</BOLD> These included: (i) attending a special event in Las Vegas, accompanied by her husband, to meet the founder of Max international; (ii) participating in a number of Max International &ldquo;Saturday Calls&rdquo;; and (iii) having weekly in-home presentations to sell Max product and recruit new Max &ldquo;associates&rdquo; to work for her. Shortly after leaving the practice, in late December 2012, she was organizing and headlining Max International promotional events on a monthly basis in the local Marriott hotel. <BOLD>[Transcript, p. 116, lines 17&ndash;30, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7-B, p. 74]</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(g) Despite being faced with numerous documents from the Max International website, posted over several years beginning in January 2013 just after her termination, many of which identified her, and rarely her husband, as a &ldquo;silver&rdquo;, &ldquo;gold&rdquo; or &ldquo;platinum&rdquo; Associate (a significant progression through the Max International organization), implying from other Max International literature <BOLD>[Max International Compensation Plan, Exhibit 23, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;234, p. 199]</BOLD> that she was generating not insignificant income from her Max International activities, she claimed that all of these were all &ldquo;typos&rdquo;. <BOLD>[Transcript, p. 120, line 7 thru p. 123, line 27, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7-B, pp. 77&ndash;80]</BOLD> Indeed, as a spokesperson and coach for Max International she appeared or starred in many YouTube video presentations since early 2013.</P1>
<P1>(h) She failed to disclose and acknowledge the &ldquo;joint&rdquo; Max International income earned during the latter part of the notice period she claims. <BOLD>[Exhibit 10, Max international back office printout, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;10, pp. 173&ndash;175; (January 1, 2013 13 through Mar 31, 2014)&mdash;the notice period awarded]</BOLD> The Learned Trial Judge failed to deduct any of this income from the damage award as mitigation income.</P1>
<P1>(i) Having also testified that she expended the effort to get her hygienists' Certificate for Self-Initiation as soon as possible after she was terminated, she did not even know that it was called a <EM>&ldquo;Certificate of Self-Initiation&rdquo;</EM> <BOLD>[see Exhibit 12, Printout from College of Dental Hygienists of Ontario Registration Database, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;12, p. 181; Transcript, p. 43, line 18 thru p. 45, line 26, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7-B, p. 46&ndash;48]</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(j) Having claimed to have sent or left resumes with more than 100 dental offices, she acknowledged that she was only able to identify a very small number of them from a calendar because she had lost her daytimer. It is a reasonable conclusion that the &ldquo;loss&rdquo; of the daytimer was because not only does it not show reasonable activity directed at finding employment as a dental hygienist but that it also would have shown extensive activity in Max International sales and promotion. The action wasn't started until well after the notice period sought had expired, yet she did not produce any mitigation documentation until after she was asked for it on discovery, more than 2 <TEXTFRAC>1/2</TEXTFRAC> years after the termination and her affidavit of documents did not claim that any documents had gone missing or been destroyed.</P1>
<P1>(k) Despite her impeccable credentials as a multilingual, restorative hygienist with a Certificate of Self-Initiation, her mitigation income reflected an extremely modest rate of success. That was obtained through working in a dental hygiene clinic run by another hygienist [Bernadette Simone], who she acknowledged, in cross-examination, she worked with in promoting Max International products in YouTube videos. <BOLD>[Transcript, p. 128, lines 1&ndash;10, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7-B, p. 81]</BOLD> She claims to have earned $3,105.63 of income as a hygienist over 12 months. <BOLD>[2013 T1 Income Tax Return, Exhibit 9A, p. 19, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-9, p. 158]</BOLD> Her total income from dental hygiene for the prior year was $59,367.00 <BOLD>[2012 T1 Income Tax Return, Exhibit 21, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;21, p. 197]</BOLD> Her 2013 stated gross income reported, represents her having worked the equivalent of only 13.6 days over the 15 month notice period she claims. That is less than 1 day per month.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>It is of some note that, although the plaintiff claims a notice period of 15 months, she only produced purported mitigation documentation for, at most, 12 months&mdash;her 2013 T1 Income Tax Return. She did not produce her 2014 Tax Return.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Yet, as reflected in her tax return, she managed to maintain two properties, her principal residence and a rental property, consistently operating as a loss according to her tax returns.</P1>
<P1>(l) Her 2013 Income Tax Return, which shows minimal total income for the entire year [$3,105.63], reflects the lease of a BMW vehicle, at a lease cost of $6,996.12 for the year, which was entered into shortly after leaving the dental practice. She claimed only 100 km of total use for the entire 2013 year [365 days] 25 km of which she claims were business use yet took $1,249.29 in deductions for business use of the vehicle.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>2013 T1 Income Tax Return, Exhibit 9A, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-9, p. 159&mdash;162</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(m) She readily acknowledged during cross-examination that she knowingly misrepresented facts concerning her activities and degree of success in regard to the Max International business in a variety of materials posted on the Max International website and in presentations, in 2013 when she claims to (a) not have been working and (b) not to be involved directly with Max International, she made on behalf of Max International's promotional activities. <BOLD>[Transcript, p. 94, line 32 thru p. 96, line 16, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7-B, pp. 65&ndash;67]</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Errors Made by the Learned Trial Judge</EM></TI>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N>1</N><TI>The Effect of the Plaintiff's Resignation in March 2005</TI>
<P>37. The appellant's first ground of appeal is that the Learned Trial Judge misconstrued and misinterpreted the facts and the law regarding the effect of the plaintiff's / respondent's resignation on March 28, 2005.</P>
<P>38. As set out above, the evidence is clear that the plaintiff formally resigned her employment. The resignation was <EM>&ldquo;clear and unequivocal&rdquo;</EM> and was accepted and her employer sought to replace her. The Trial Judge's reliance on the lack of materiality of the employer's cost to run a newspaper ad is a red herring. A key source of applicants was, in fact, from the Ontario Hygienists Association which did not charge for their advertising. The employer accepted the resignation and went through the process of seeking candidates to replace Ms. Theberge.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Kieran v. Ingram Micro Inc.</SOC><CITE>2004 CanLII 4852</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at para 27</BOLD> <UNDER>&lt;http://canlii.ca/t/1hkjm&gt;</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>39. There is no evidence before the court, and there is not any issue pled by the plaintiff / respondent, to suggest that the plaintiff's subsequent employment, commencing on Monday, July 11, 2005 was anything other than the commencement of a new contractual arrangement.</P>
<P>40. There is nothing to support any suggestion of the revocation or withdrawal of the resignation. Rather, as admitted by the plaintiff / respondent, and as acknowledged by the Learned Trial Judge, Ms. Theberge entered into a new contract of employment. Contrary to the Judge's suggestion that there was no consideration to support a new contract being established, Dr. Kutcher's answer on cross-examination that the consideration for the contract was <EM>&ldquo;a job&rdquo;</EM> is a full and proper answer to both the question and the issue. The Learned Trial Judge's statement that <EM>&ldquo;Her resignation was rescinded well prior to July 7, 2005&rdquo;</EM> <BOLD>[Reasons for Judgment at para 29]</BOLD> is unsupported by the facts or the evidence.</P>
<P>41. It is submitted that the Learned Trial Judge made a palpable and overriding error in this regard. In consequence:
<P1>a) because the parties did not expressly agree / contract otherwise, Ms. Theberge's tenure commenced effective Monday, July 11, 2005; and</P1>
<P1>b) the employment agreement executed by the parties on that date, and its terms and conditions, <BOLD>[Exhibit 3, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-3, pp. 146&ndash;148],</BOLD> including the termination provision in that agreement, governed the employment relationship thereafter.</P1></P>
<P>42. The foregoing submissions are supported by the August 31, 2018 decision of Justice Edwards in <CASEREF><SOC>English v. Manulife Financial Corporation</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 5135 (CanLII)</CITE></CASEREF>. <UNDER>&lt;http://canlii.ca/t/htr7r&gt;</UNDER> In his Reasons for Decision, Justice Edwards conducted a thorough review of the law on the issue of an employee's ability to rescind a voluntary resignation.</P>
<P>43. Specifically, Justice Edwards held that the requirement that an individual could rescind a resignation unless the employer had relied, to its detriment, on the resignation was not the law of Ontario and that the statement found in the Court of Appeal's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Kieran v. Ingram Micro Inc.</SOC><CITE>2004 (CanLII) 4852</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> [at para 34] <UNDER>&lt;http://canlii.ca/t/1hkjm&gt;</UNDER> was obiter and <EM>&ldquo;The law in my view has evolved, and is now more a reflection of basic contract law&rdquo;</EM>, [at para 30] In support of this conclusion Justice Edwards referred to decisions of the Nova Scotia and Newfoundland and Labrador Courts of Appeal and another decision of the Ontario Superior Court of Justice.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Kerr v. Valley Volkswagen</SOC><CITE>2015 NSCA 7 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>11, 12 and 20</PARANUM></CASEREF> <UNDER>&lt;http://canlii.ca/t/qg35f&gt;</UNDER></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Avalon Ford Sales (1996) Limited v. Evans</SOC><CITE>2017 NLCA 9 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>30&ndash;37</PARANUM></CASEREF> <UNDER>&lt;http://canlii.ca/t/gx8t3&gt;</UNDER></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Johal v. Simmons da Silva LLP</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 7835 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>30, 70, 71 and 97</PARANUM></CASEREF> <UNDER>&lt;http://canlii.ca/t/gw1xx&gt;</UNDER></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N>2</N><TI>Credibility Issues Concerning the Plaintiff's Evidence</TI>
<P>44. Despite acknowledging that the appellant's counsel had raised numerous issues regarding the plaintiff's credibility during trial, and in submissions <BOLD>[Reasons for Judgment at para 53 and Transcript, p. 118, line 28 thru p. 119, line 5, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7-B, pp. 75 - 76].</BOLD> The Learned Trial Judge failed to address, in making her decision, the impact of the issues put forward by the appellant in this regard. As set out above [see sub-paras 36 (a) - (m)] the appellant raised, at trial, many significant matters which clearly demonstrated serious issues regarding the plaintiff's credibility. The Learned Trial Judge refers to this submission at paragraph 53 of her Reasons. However, she failed to properly address the credibility issues, even in a cursory manner.</P>
<P>45. It is important to note that the Learned Trial Judge does not make any findings adverse to any of the credibility of any of the appellant's witnesses. At best, she says that she accepts the plaintiff's evidence, even where it is in stark contrast to documentary evidence accepted into evidence without any contradiction being offered.</P>
<P>46. The appellant submits that the Learned Trial Judge's failure to properly and adequately address this issue constitutes reversible error.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N>3</N><TI>The Failure to Properly Calculate the Respondent's Damages</TI>
<P>47. The respondent did not properly prove her damages. Specifically:
<P1>a) she pled the same figure for both her annual income figure and for the 15 month notice period she claimed;</P1>
<P1>b) the only documentary evidence she tendered was her T4 Statement of Remuneration Paid for 2012 <BOLD>[Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Exhibit 8, Tab 8-8, p. 155]</BOLD> but offered no submissions to explain the number&mdash;the evidence was that her earnings varied based upon the hours she actually worked;</P1>
<P1>c) she acknowledged having started full time work with a dentist [Dr. Maini] in March 2014&mdash;within the notice period claimed <BOLD>[Transcript, p. 32, line 27 thru p. 33, line 7, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7-B, p. 41 - 42];</BOLD></P1>
<P1>d) she did not produce proper evidence of or quantum for income from 2014, including whatever she earned from working for Dr. Maini in March 2014; and</P1>
<P1>e) she did however produce some evidence of income received jointly by her and her husband for February and March 2014 [within the notice period&mdash;<BOLD>Exhibit 10 at trial, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;10, p. 173]</BOLD> but with the bulk of the notice period having the Max International payments / income statement with the payee information removed and substantial 2013 income attributable to her and/or her husband&mdash;<BOLD>Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;10 pp. 173&ndash;175;</BOLD> Exhibit 10 was a document the plaintiff / respondent downloaded from the Max International website.
<P2><BOLD>Transcript, evidence in chief&mdash;p. 38, line 25 thru p. 40, line 17, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7-B, pp. 43&ndash;45; cross-examination at p. 91, lines 10&ndash;20, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 7-B, p. 64</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>48. While the Learned Trial Judge did deduct from the damage award the modest amount of income the respondent reported on her 2013 T1 General Income Tax Return, she did not deduct: (a) the statutory termination pay which was paid to the respondent <BOLD>[Exhibit 18, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;18, pp. 189 - 190]</BOLD> by Kutcher Dentistry Professional Corporation; or any of the joint income earned by the respondent and her husband from Max International <BOLD>[Exhibit 10, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;10, pp. 173&ndash;175].</BOLD> As such, the respondent was overcompensated in the award of damages made.</P>
<P>49. The appellant submits that the foregoing also constitutes reversible error.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3 LABEL="Issue"><N>4</N><TI>The Plaintiff's Failure to Properly or Adequately Mitigate</TI>
<P>50. At paragraph 51 of the Reasons for Judgment the Learned Trial Judge stated:
<QUOTE><P><EM>[51] The plaintiff presented no physical evidence of her mitigation efforts. She testified that she lost her day timer and was only able to identify a small fraction of her efforts</EM>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>51. It is submitted that the failure to properly weigh and consider all of the evidence, and particularly the inconsistencies and contradictions contained within the respondent's evidence during trial reflects and represents a palpable and overriding error justifying intervention by this Court.</P>
<P>52. It is unbelievable that's someone with the respondent's credentials could not find an employment position or more freelance / independent contract work reflecting less than 1 day per month during the 15 month notice period she claimed.</P>
<P>53. Curiously, at the end of the notice period claimed, the end of March 2014, not only does she acknowledge having found fully mitigating employment but that, just prior to that date [the middle of February 2014&mdash;see <BOLD>Exhibit 10&mdash;printout from Max International &ldquo;backoffice&rdquo; file on monies paid to Jasmine Theberge and / or Hughcliffe Lindsay, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;10 at page 173]</BOLD> she acknowledges that she began receiving compensation, jointly with her husband, from Max International. This, coupled with what came out during her cross-examination regarding her involvement with Max International, since early 2010&mdash;without any attributed income, belies her version of what took place after her termination by Kutcher Dentistry Professional Corporation. By September 2014, barely 7 months after the end of the notice period, the business was entirely hers <BOLD>[see Exhibit 10, Appeal Book and Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;10, at page 171]</BOLD> without her providing any compensation to her husband. Her testimony was that her ex-husband walked away from it and gave her the business. This suggests that, along with the many You Tube videos she acknowledged making on behalf of Max International, and the recognition of &ldquo;gold level&rdquo; performance that she (and she alone) received from Max International, it was always her business. It also supports the proposition that she diverted or continued to divert the income to her husband, although the evidence demonstrates that neither of them reported any of the Max International income for income tax purposes. <BOLD>[Reasons for Judgment at paras 55&ndash;57]</BOLD> At a minimum, the Learned Trial Judge acknowledges that the plaintiff / respondent received mitigation income in the last two months of the notice period yet that income was not disclosed by her and it was not considered in the assessment of her damages. <BOLD>[Reasons at para 55]</BOLD></P>
<P>54. Moreover, the paucity of the plaintiff's evidence on her mitigation efforts also belies her position and adds more doubt to her credibility on this and all other issues. Her evidence on her mitigation efforts was limited to the following.
