<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Summary and Conclusion</EM></TI>
<P>55. The plaintiff executed 3 employment agreements containing the same termination language she challenges in this proceeding.
<P1>a) <BOLD>May 5, 1999&mdash;Exhibit 1&mdash;Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-1, pp. 142&ndash;144</BOLD></P1>
<P1>b) <BOLD>June 30, 2005&mdash;Exhibit 3&mdash;Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-3, pp. 146&ndash;48</BOLD></P1>
<P1>c) <BOLD>December 22, 2011&mdash;Exhibit 6&mdash;Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-6, pp. 151&ndash;153</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>56. On March 28, 2005, the plaintiff resigned her employment. <BOLD>Exhibit 2, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-2, pp. 142&ndash;144.</BOLD> Her resignation was accepted. She subsequently requested that she be hired again. Merren Kutcher and Dr. Kutcher discussed the matter and decided to offer her employment and she signed a new employment agreement on June 30, 2005. <BOLD>[Exhibit 3, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-3, pp. 146&ndash;148]</BOLD> Without that new employment agreement she would not have had employment.</P>
<P>57. Via letter dated October 1, 2011 she was provided with 3 months advance formal notice of the termination of her employment. <BOLD>[Exhibit 16, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;16, p. 187]</BOLD> On December 22, 2011, after receiving independent legal advice and negotiating changes to the document, the plaintiff executed the third employment agreement. <BOLD>[Exhibit 6, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;6, pp. 151&mdash;153]</BOLD></P>
<P>58. In mid-March 2012, the plaintiff confirmed in writing <BOLD>[Exhibit 17, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;17, p. 188]</BOLD> that she and two other hygienists had obtained legal advice concerning the proposed new employment contract they were asked to sign in late December 2011 and which she subsequently signed on December 22, 2011&mdash;<BOLD>[Exhibit 6, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8-6, pp. 151&ndash;153]</BOLD></P>
<P>59. She received notice of termination on December 20, 2012. This action was commenced on December 3, 2014.</P>
<P>60. The defendant submits that, based upon all of the foregoing, the plaintiff was lawfully terminated on December 20, 2012. At the time she was <BOLD>contractually</BOLD> entitled, <BOLD>by mutual agreement</BOLD>, to one week of notice or pay in lieu of notice, the latter of which she received.</P>
<P>61. In the alternative, the defendant submits that, if the employment agreements are unenforceable and ineffective, the plaintiff's termination occurred as a result of the October 1, 2011 notice of termination <BOLD>[Exhibit 16, Appeal Book &amp; Compendium, Tab 8&ndash;16, p. 187].</BOLD> The plaintiff received 3 months of working notice and remained employed by the defendant for the ensuing 12 months and therefore received a total of 15 months of effective notice. In the result, the plaintiff has no further claim or at most a claim for minimal additional notice at the end of 2012.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;Order Sought</TI>
<P>62. The appellant requests an Order setting aside the trial decision, dismissing the action and awarding it the costs of the appeal and the action.</P>
<P>63. In the alternative, the appellant requests an Order varying the Judgment in accordance with the determination(s) made by this Court.</P>
<P><BOLD>All of which is respectfully submitted.</BOLD></P>
